description: From Middle English wowen, woȝen, from Old English wōgian (“to woo, court, marry”), of uncertain origin. Cognate with Scots wow (“to woo”). Perhaps related to Old English wōg, wōh (“bending, crookedness”), in the specific sense of "bend or incline (some)one toward oneself". If so, then derived from Proto-Germanic *wanhō (“a bend, angle”), from Proto-Indo-European *wonk- (“crooked, bent”), from Proto-Indo-European *wā- (“to bend, twist, turn”); related to Old Norse vá (“corner, angle”).

verbs.description: woo (third-person singular simple present woos, present participle wooing, simple past and past participle wooed)

entries.meaning: (transitive) To endeavor to gain someone's support.
(transitive) (often of a man) To try to persuade (someone) to be in an amorous relationship with
examples: Each, like the Grecian artist, wooes  / The image he himself has wrought.

entries.meaning: (transitive) To court solicitously; to invite with importunity.
examples: I woo the wind / That still delays his coming.

adjectives.description: woo (comparative more woo, superlative most woo)
